sANBDWZpHg4.title: Low Cross vs Normal Cross
sANBDWZpHg4.description:
Normal Cross vs Low Driven Cross

For the normal cross I approach the ball so that my body is positioned almost straight ahead to the endline, but just slightly angled towards the goal. I try to lean back slightly. My foot/ankle is not locked out straight, but just wider than 90 degrees. I try to make contact with the part of my foot that is in between the inside part of the foot and the laces and I imagine hitting just lower than the outside center of the ball, wrapping my foot around the football. My follow through goes over past my left leg, but I try to keep the follow through relatively low and short. 

For the low cross I approach the ball so that my body is positioned almost straight ahead to the endline, but just slightly angled towards the goal. I try to lean more over the ball. My foot/ankle is not locked out straight, but just wider than 90 degrees. I try to make contact with the part of my foot that is in between the inside part of the foot and the laces and I imagine hitting the outside center of the ball, wrapping my foot around the football. My follow through goes over past my left leg, but I try to keep the follow through very low and short and try to really follow through with my momentum over the ball.

6Qk3rkUfXIA.title: Did I Make a Mistake Playing Collegiate Soccer?
6Qk3rkUfXIA.description:
Obviously nobody has a the ability to see how their life would have panned out if they made a different decision, but after playing college in the U.S., semi-professionally in the U.S. and abroad in Germany/New Zealand, and professionally in the states I am very confident that I made the right decision for me.

Is that the right decision for everybody? Absolutely not. There are countless teenagers where after talking with them, I’ve pushed them to skip college and pursue the semi-pro or pro route domestically or abroad. 

You have to look at your situation, your opportunities, your goals for your playing career and life post footy, and make the best decision for you. #BecomeElite

Will training with a small ball or a size 1 soccer ball still get you to improve? Yes, definitely. I love incorporating a smaller soccer ball in my first touch sessions or tight space dribbling sessions to improve my touch and control of the ball. Now, you shouldn't ALWAYS train with a small ball, because I'm a firm believer in that you should practice how you play, but still there are huge benefits to training with a smaller sized soccer ball especially in terms of developing control/touch.

In this video, I want to inform many of you of a big misconception among many athletes, coaches, trainers, etc. This conception is that the reason you are sore the next day or two after a strenuous workout is because of the lactic acid building up in your muscles and somehow causing the soreness the following day. 

Although Lactic Acid does contribute to a burning sensation DURING the workout, lactic acid has nothing to do with the delayed onset muscle soreness you feel after a workout. 

Watch and learn what Lactic Acid really does and how it actually is there to try to NOT get your body sore the next day.

In this Two Minute Tuesday, I talk about how there is an overemphasis of keeping your head up in soccer. I constantly was told to keep my head up while dribbling or playing all the time and it actually lead to a lot of confusion for me as a young player. 

I this video, I analyze the game footage of some of the best players in the world like Cristiano Ronaldo, Messi, Steven Gerrard, and show you how these players alter their positioning and line of sight depending on different situations in the game.

92pz01_JZvY.title: How to Study Soccer Games to Improve at Your Position
92pz01_JZvY.description:
FOLLOW ME!
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/mattsheldon23/
Become Elite on Instagram: @Become_Elite

Today's video is all an example video of how I study soccer games in order to improve at my position of right back. I take a professional soccer game at the highest level (Bundesliga, EPL, La Liga) and I just watch and learn from the player in my position. 

In this video, I study Borussia Mochengladbach vs FC Bayern Munich and just watch Jantschke play. I study his movements, off ball patterns, passing decisions, defensive positioning to try to learn from him. 

My hope for this video is to teach you how I learn, so that you can take these same skills and apply them to a different professional soccer match so you can learn from a different player who plays in your specific position. Let me know what you think!

Bhgxor2vP7U.title: How a Pro Soccer Player Cured His Patellar Tendinitis
Bhgxor2vP7U.description:
FOLLOW ME!
Snapchat: become_elite
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/mattsheldon23/
Become Elite on Instagram: @Become_Elite

Below is MY rehab regimen, I am not saying this is how you should recover from your patellar tendinitis as everyone recovers at different speeds. I was always listening to my body, tracking how I felt, and making the next day's workout dependent on that. 

My Rehab Regimen:

Day 1-10: Stopped all weightlifting, soccer, and running activities, rested as much as possible, iced 3-5x a day for 20 minutes. My goal was to rest until 
Day 11-18: Introduced static stretching and light bodyweight exercises as long as it didn't hurt my knee and make it worse the next day. If knee felt better than the day before, I progressively made each workout harder than the previous by adding more sets, reps, or time.
Day 19-28: Started to introduce biking to the workout regimen. Progressively making each biking session harder than the previous if knee allowed so. Continued to stretch and preform bodyweight workouts. 
Day 29-40: Started to introduce light jogging and running workouts. Stopped biking, but continued to stretch. Again, made each workout harder than the last as long as knee responded well and felt stronger. Started to also add weight to all exercises and progressively added more and more weight with each workout. 
Day 41-48: Started to add soccer training sessions to the workout regimen. Continued to stretch, perform exercises with increasingly heavier weights, and continued to make each running workout harder than the last. Made each soccer training session slightly more rigorous than the last.
Day 49+: Started Preseason with Saint Louis FC. Stopped personal soccer training and running sessions, but continued to stretch and perform exercises with added weight.

iEZJkdtlSHs.description:
FOLLOW ME!
Snapchat: become_elite
Instagram: https://www.instagram.com/mattsheldon23/

Bodyweight Workout Program:
(15-20 second rest between each exercise)
1. Hanging Knee Raise - 30 reps
2. Neutral Grip Pull-Ups - 20 reps
3. Diamond Push-Ups - 30 reps
4. Quick Jumping Lunges - 10 reps each leg
5. Handstand Push-Ups - 5 Reps
6. Squat Jumps - 20 reps
7. V-Ups - 20 reps
8. Supermans - 30 reps
9. Burpees - 30 reps
10. Wide Grip Chair Push-Ups - 20 reps
11. 5 minute Break
12. Repeat entire workout one more time.

Become Elite's 5 Essential Passing Drills Every Player Should Master

Overview:
1. Gated Passing - 1 and 2 Touch (50 Passes R/L)
2. Looped Passing - Clockwise and Counter-Clockwise (30 Passes R/L)
3. Driven Ball Passing (20 Passes R/L)
4. Two Touch Box Drill (20 Passes R/L)
5. Long Ball Passing (15 Passes R/L)

By doing this drills every single week, I can guarantee that you will improve your passing accuracy, power, and precision. It all comes down to how much work you are willing to put in.

OT0LsGherZo.description:
ADD me on Snapchat: become_elite

FOLLOW me on Instagram: @Mattsheldon23
FOLLOW us on Instagram: @Become_Elite
VISIT our Website: http://www.become-elite.com

Today, we are answering 30 of your questions that were sent in via our Instagram page @Become_Elite!

Questions:

1. Do you think that you’ll leave OC Blues when your contract is up or do you think you’ll get an extension?
2. How do you play against players that are bigger and faster than you?
3. Should you do individual training during season?
4. How is the Glucosamine working for the ankles/joints?
5. Are you still following your diet?
6. Have you played against anyone who went pro?
7. Where do you see yourself in 5 years?
8. Did you ever think about giving up? If so, how did you push through it?
9.  How did you deal with coaches yelling at you?
10. What got you into doing YouTube videos?
11. How was your entire high school career?
12. When you were in Germany did you feel homesick?
13. Would you take an offer to the NASL over the OC Blues if you had one? 
14. How old were you when you realized you could make a career in soccer?
15. What has been the best moment of your career?
16. What is your squat, bench, and deadlift max? Are you living your dream?
17.  Do you lift or do speed training when in season?
18. What do you love most about being a professional footballer?
19.  How did you get past your toughest times when trying to make it?
20. How do I know if I am good enough to play D1 or D2 soccer?

Many of you guys have asked for a tutorial/tips/advice on how to cross a soccer ball. This is also known as a whipped in cross, a curler, a curve kick, bending the ball, etc. Here is what goes through my head when I attempt to preform this type of kick. 

How to Cross a Soccer Ball:
1. Keep the ball on the outside of your body while dribbling straight down the sideline.
2. Tap the ball 30 degrees in to the center of the field 3-5 yards before you want to whip in the cross.
3. Open up your hips into the center of the field slightly.
4. Plant your foot closer than normal to the the ball to allow for the ball to roll away from you as your swing your leg. 
5. Make contact in between the laces and the instep, in what I call the "Inside Laces."

Become Elite's Best Drills to Improve your Weak Foot

Any drill will improve your weak foot, there are no drills that will improve your weak foot faster than any other drills. If you want to improve your weak footed shot, then take shots with your weak foot. If you want to get your first touch of your weak foot better, then trap the ball more with your weak foot. It might sound obvious and might not be the answer you are looking for, but it is the answer you need to hear.

Soccer Training

10 yd Dribbling Drill:
Roll, Tap, Tap, Roll - 4 sets, 20 second rest
Brazilian Sole (Right Foot) - 2 sets, 20 second rest
Brazilian Sole (Left Foot) - 2 sets, 20 second rest
Brazilian Sole (2 feet) - 2 sets, 20 second rest
Inside, Outside - 3 sets, 20 second rest

Zig Zag Cone Weave
Right Foot Only - 4 sets, 45 seconds
Left Foot Only - 4 sets, 45 seconds
Inside Turns Only - 4 sets, 45 seconds
Outside Turns Only - 4 sets, 45 seconds

Shuttle Run (5, 10, 15, 20)
Inside Cuts (R) - 1 set, 60 second rest
Outside Cuts (R) - 1 set, 60 second rest
Cruyff Turns (R) - 1 set, 60 second rest
Rivelino Turns (R) - 1 set, 60 second rest
Pull-Back Taps (R) - 1 set, 60 second rest
Repeat all with (L) foot. 

Round the Circle
Right Foot - 4 sets, 45 second rest
Left Foot - 4 sets, 45 second rest

TRAINING PROGRAMS: www.become-elite.com
FOLLOW US ON INSTAGRAM: @Become_Elite
FOLLOW ME ON INSTAGRAM: @Mattsheldon23

Matt from Become Elite shows us a typical training session he does when training individually/by himself. In the video, the exact drills, times, reps, sets, and rest are described.

Training Session Overview:
1. 200 Below Knee Alternating Juggles
2. 100 Below Knee Juggles with Right
3.100 Below Knee Juggles with Left
4. 200 Waist Height Alternating Juggles
5. 100 Waist Height Juggles with Right
6. 100 Waist Height Juggles with Left
7. 100 Juggles to Ten then High Kick
8. 100 Juggles to Ten then ATW
9. Full Field Sprint at 80%
10. 4 Full Field Sprints at 100% with Ball
11. 2 Shuttle Runs (5, 10, 15, 20) with Right Foot
12. 2 Shuttle Runs (5, 10, 15, 20) with Left Foot
13. 100 1 Touch Passes with Right
14. 100 1 Touch Passes with Left
15. 3-5 minutes of 2 Touch Passing
16. 20 Laced Shots on Goal with Right
17. 20 Laced Shots on Goal with Left

Matt from Become Elite shows us a typical training session he does when training individually/by himself. In the video, the exact drills, times, reps, sets, and rest are described.

Training Session Overview:
1. 2-3 minute warm-up with dynamic movements
2. Box Juggling | Zig Zag Cone Weave | Gated Pass (10 sets each foot)
3. Looped Dribbling (5 sets each foot)
4. Zig Zag Attacking Moves | Far Post Curled Shot (7 sets each foot)
5. First Touch Drill Off Fence (5 minutes or 30 reps)
6. Roll to Shot with Cones (20 shots each foot)
7. Freestyle Juggling (5-10 minutes)

THE BLUEPRINT: http://become-elite.com/standard-prog...

VISIT our Website: http://www.become-elite.com

So many people have asked for a tutorial on how to shoot a soccer/football with power, strength, accuracy, and precision. Here is the Become Elite tutorial on how to do it!

Steps:
1. Approach the ball 45 degrees
2. Keep your chest up and pointed at target
3. Have a slight lean away from the ball with arm up for balance
4. Make contact on the ball 1-2 inches below exact center
5. Position your foot so that your heel is up, toes down, foot 45 degrees, and the side of your big toe brushing the ground.

So many people have asked for a tutorial on how to shoot a soccer/football with power, strength, accuracy, and precision. Here is the Become Elite tutorial on how to do it!

Steps:
1. Approach the ball 45 degrees
2. Keep your chest up and pointed at target
3. Have a slight lean away from the ball with arm up for balance
4. Make contact on the ball 1-2 inches below exact center
5. Position your foot so that your heel is up, toes down, foot 45 degrees, and the side of your big toe brushing the ground.

Many of you guys have asked for a tutorial/tips/advice on how to curl a soccer ball. This is also known as a banana kick, a curler, a curve kick, bending the ball, etc. Here is what goes through my head when I attempt to preform this type of kick. 

How to Curve a Soccer Ball:
1. Approach the ball from 30 degrees instead of 45 degrees. 
2. Determine where on the ball to strike it depending on what type of kick you want to do. 
3. Determine where on your foot you need to strike the ball depending on the type of kick you want to do.
4. Determine your upper body position depending on the type of curl you want the ball to do.

Matt from Become Elite shows us a typical training session he does when he has access to a wall and is training individually/by himself. In the video, the exact drills, times, reps, sets, and rest are described.

Training Session Overview:
1. 100 1-touch passes with right foot
2. 100 1-touch passes with left foot.
3. 100 2-touch passes with right foot.
4. 100 2-touch passes with left foot.
5. 5 minutes of 1-touch wall juggling.
6. 5-10 minutes of 2-touch laced strikes from 20 yards back.
7. 20 turns to the left off wall pass.
8. 20 turns to the right off wall pass.
5. 20 turns to backward right off wall pass.
6. 20 turns to backwards left off wall pass.
7. 5-10 minutes of 1-touch laced volley's against wall.

C6xPIZdCML8.title: How to Do A Foot Stall (Football/Soccer Freestyle Trick)
C6xPIZdCML8.description:
The Become Elite beginner's guide to performing the basic foot stall!

A foot stall is a freestyle trick where you balance the ball on top of your laces. This move can be done either when picking up the ball off of a roll or can be caught out of the air while juggling. The higher the ball is dropped from the more difficult this trick is. 

This guide will teach you the fundamentals of how to stall the soccer ball on your foot

Overview:
1. Raise your foot off of the ground and relax your toes. They should not be flexed up, nor down. 
2. Allow the ball to fall and hit the top of your toe box. 
3. If your toes are relaxed you will cushion the ball so that it doesn't bounce upwards or off your foot.
4. Flex your toes upwards, to get the ball to roll back on to your laces.
5. Continue to squeeze your toes upwards to hold the ball in place between your shin and laces. 
6. Balance the ball, by moving side to side.

t4OLSQu2aGE.title: How to do a Chest Stall (Soccer/Football Freestyle)
t4OLSQu2aGE.description:
Become Elite's tutorial on how to perform the perfect chest stall while juggling/freestyling!

A chest stall is a freestyle trick that involves hitting/lifting the ball up and towards you then leaning underneath and catching the ball on your chest. You then can stall the ball in the position for however long you want to.

Overview:
1. Lift or hit the ball about head height with little to no spin.
2. Widen your feet and lean backwards as far as you can underneath the ball.
3. As the ball descends to your chest, lean further to cushion the ball.
3.5. Position your body so that the ball is landing towards one side of your chest and catch it on the upper chest/collarbone/nape of the neck.
4. Lift up your arms and squeeze your chest together so that you can better hold the ball.
5. Stay leaning back to create a flat platform to hold the ball.

lHy5-QofzP0.title: How to Do the Around the World (Soccer/Football Freestyle Trick)
lHy5-QofzP0.description:
Become Elite's Ultimate Guide to Performing the Around the World.

The Around the World is a football/soccer/futbol trick that involves juggling the ball and while doing so, moving your foot completely over and back under the ball before it touches the ground. 

Trick Overview:
1. Start with alternating, below knee juggles.
2. When ready, hit the ball on the side to produce a slight side spin and hit it just below waist height.
3. As you do so, continue your path inwards and upwards.
4. When the ball is at it's highest point, your leg should be completely over the ball.
5. Quickly bring your foot back under the ball on the opposite side, slow your foot, and catch it before it hits the ground.
6. Make sure to practice!

Learning Overview:
1. Start by just practicing the side sweeping kick to get used to continuing your trajectory upwards after a juggle.
2. Practice what I call Half-Around the World's off the bounce.
3. Start trying to quicken your Around the World, so that there is no need for a bounce.
4. Put it all together.

E3sjcv0m1z4.title: How to Hit a Long Ball in Soccer/Football
E3sjcv0m1z4.description:
Become Elite's Tutorial on How to hit along ball in Soccer/Football with accuracy, back spin, and pace!

A long ball means that you strike the ball with your laces in such a way that it flies in the air to your intended target about 30-60 yards away. The kick is usually intended to be straight, high above the ground, with power and with a slight backspin.

Overview:
1. Approach the ball at a 45 degree angle
2. Plant your foot as you normally would, pointed at your target
3. Turn your knee slightly out and lean back as you strike through
4. Make contact with the toe/bottom of the laces on your foot.
5. Strike the ball so that there is a little backspin and it flies straight through the air
6. Follow through and do not land on your kicking foot.

vNsqMKT98Ms.title: How to Lace a Soccer Ball on the Ground
vNsqMKT98Ms.description:
Become Elite's Tutorial on How to Lace a Soccer/Football on the ground with accuracy and pace!

Lacing a ball on the ground means that you strike the ball with your laces in such a way that it skims over the ground, sometimes this kick is referred to as a worm burner or a driven ball. 

Overview:
1. Approach the ball at a 45 degree angle
2. Plant your foot as you normally would, pointed at your target
3. Turn your knee in and keep it over the ball as you strike through
4. Make contact with the toe/bottom of the laces on your foot.
5. Strike the ball so that there is a little backspin and it skims across the ground
6. Follow through and stay over it to keep the ball low.

9N-sb8dmKoA.title: Top 3 Soccer Dribbling Moves You Need to Know
9N-sb8dmKoA.description:
Become Elite's Top Three Soccer/Football Dribbling Moves Every Player Should Master

The Stepover:
The stepover is great move when you have space and want to go 1v1 against a defender.
1. Approach the defender straight on so that you can go either way around him/her.
(If you want to go to the right, keep the ball on the left side of your body.)
2. When you get about 3-4 feet away from your defender start to perform the move.
3. Swing your left leg in front of the ball and plant it on the left side of the ball.
5. Dip your shoulders down and to the left to get the defender thinking you are going that way.
6. Push out the ball 45 degrees to the right using the outside of your right foot.
7. Switch the feet if you want to go the other way.

Drag and Go:
The Drag and Go is a great move when in slightly tighter space and when you are not running at full speed at a defender. 
1. Approach the defender as you normally would so that you could go either way around him. 
2. Angle your body so that you are almost sideways. One shoulder should be pointed at the defender and the other almost behind you.
3. Drag the ball with the inside of your trailing foot, all your weight should be on your front foot.
4. Take a few small steps and when ready dip your shoulders and explode the opposite direction.
5. Push the ball with the outside of your trail foot.

Maradona:
The Maradona is a move to get out of an oncoming 50-50 tackle, it should not be done as a 1v1 move!
1. The ball should be about equidistant from you and the defender, hence the 50-50 tackle scenario.
2. Quickly approach the ball and get there before the defender does.
3. Pull the ball back with your right foot away from the defender.
4. As you do this start turning backside left so that your back shoulder is leading the spin. 
5. Simultaneously, plant your right foot and sweep the ball with your left foot to continue your spin
6. You should almost make a full rotation with your body and now be past the defender. 
7. Explode off into space

rcUHPII18dg.title: The 1000 Juggle Workout Plan
rcUHPII18dg.description:
Become Elite's 1000 Juggle Workout.

Juggling is the act of keeping up the soccer ball in the air using everything on your body except for your hands or arms. The best/most practical way to do so is by using your feet. Juggling with your feet is a intermediate soccer skill that will help you with your touch and control of the ball. All the best soccer/football players in the world know how to consistently keep the ball up.

This guide will walk you through a juggling training program that will make you juggle the ball over 1000 times.

ALL EXERCISES ARE CUMULATIVE. IF YOU GET 16 JUGGLES, THEN DROP IT, START COUNTING AT 17! JUGGLES DO NOT RESET ON A MESS UP.

Overview:
1. Hands to Right Foot - 25 Juggles
2. Hands to Left Foot - 25 Juggles
3. Hands to Right then Left Foot - 25 Juggles
4. Hands to Left then Right Foot - 25 Juggles
5. Right Foot Below Knee - 100 Juggles
6. Left Foot Below Knee - 100 Juggles
7. Alternating Feet Below Knee - 200 Juggles
8. Right Foot Above Waist - 100 Juggles
9. Left Foot Above Waist - 100 Juggles
10. Alternating Feet Above Waist - 200 Juggles
11. Seated Juggles - 100 Juggles

Total - 1000 Juggles

AmUujhQR1Ag.title: The Beginner's Tutorial to Soccer/Football Juggling
AmUujhQR1Ag.description:
The Become Elite beginner's guide to juggling a soccer ball!

Juggling is the act of keeping up the soccer ball in the air using everything on your body except for your hands or arms. The best/most practical way to do so is by using your feet. Juggling with your feet is a intermediate soccer skill that will help you with your touch and control of the ball. All the best soccer/football players in the world know how to consistently keep the ball up.

This guide will teach you the fundamentals of how to juggle the soccer ball.

Overview:
1. There are two ways to juggle the ball using your feet; with the laces and with the toe box.
2. When juggling with the laces, kick out your foot, point your toes, and hit the ball directly square off of your laces so that the ball pops straight up in the air.
3. When juggling with your toe box, keep the ball closer to your body, instead of kicking out, lift up your knee slightly, and make contact on top of your toes squarely in the center of the ball.
4. In either method, try to keep the ball at a consistent height and tempo so that it is easier to control and continue juggling.
